# Psalms GABC Development Rule

Use these conventions for all psalm first-verse chant work.

## Marker semantics

- `gr1` = accented note group; map accented sung syllables here first.
- `gr` = extra note group for non-accent extension notes.
- Neutral notes are fixed tone material and must not consume accent slots.
- If a cadence cannot be mapped cleanly, fall back to text rendering.

## Tone table location and naming

- Keep chant tone tables in `psalms-ctan/tex/lualatex/psalms/psalmtones.lua`.
- Reuse existing preset keys exactly (`1D`, `4E`, `8G`, `8G-star`, `peregrinus`).
- Store raw gabc cadence fragments with marker tokens for flex/mediant/termination.
- Do not introduce ad-hoc key aliases unless all call sites are updated.

## Text and chant cadence sync

- Text-render and chant-render must share cadence-selection logic.
- Any change to accent or syllable tokenization must be reflected in gabc mapping behavior.
- Keep non-chant output byte-for-byte stable unless a change is explicitly intended.

## Minimum regression checks

Run/verify at least:

- Non-chant mode: representative tones still format verses correctly.
- Chant mode: verse 1 emits only `\gabcsnippet{...}` when enabled.
- Fallback path: missing gabc preset or mapping failure reverts verse 1 to text.
- Representative tones include at least `1D`, `4E`, `8G`, and `peregrinus`.
